        "en": "For 2026, BTS's complete group return and an 82-show world tour form the primary earnings catalysts, with some sell-side analysts projecting full-year revenue approaching KRW 4 trillion and operating profit recovering to the KRW 510–530 billion range—representing a near ten-fold improvement versus 2025. The world tour's adoption of dynamic pricing and 360-degree open staging in North American venues is expected to maximize per-show attendance and average ticket prices, while supply-constrained MD and licensing demand tied to the tour is set to amplify indirect revenue throughout the cycle. Weverse's transition into sustained profitability places it in an earnings-leveraged phase where incremental MAU growth and transaction volume flow disproportionately to the operating line, with BTS's re-engagement and new artist onboarding expected to reinforce the upward trajectory. Over the medium term, localization acts such as KATSEYE and COTES are building fan bases in North America and Latin America, providing structural diversification away from BTS—though initial investment costs are likely to remain a headwind in the near term before these IPs reach scale. The three-year shareholder return policy, with a minimum guaranteed DPS of KRW 500 based on FCF, signals improved capital discipline and represents the first minimum dividend guarantee by a Korean content company, providing a floor for return expectations. Nonetheless, until Chairman Bang's legal situation is resolved, governance uncertainty will likely cap near-term multiple expansion, making quarterly margin recovery the most critical operating metric to monitor. Visibility into the post-BTS-tour earnings cycle from 2027 onward remains limited and represents the most significant medium-term uncertainty for investors with longer holding horizons."
